    "## Part 1 — DBSCAN-Built ThresholdsV2\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why V1 thresholds fell short\n",
    "\n",
    "Legacy Steps 1–4 use hand-crafted or naively computed min/max price bands. A single\n",
    "extreme transaction widens a V1 band to the point of uselessness — or, when data is\n",
    "sparse, the range is too tight to match new, slightly-different prices.\n",
    "\n",
    "### What DBSCAN does differently\n",
    "\n",
    "**DBSCAN** (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise) scans the full\n",
    "purchase history for a product and groups prices into **tight, organically-shaped clusters**\n",
    "while ignoring statistical outliers as noise. Each resulting ThresholdV2 record captures:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Field | What it stores |\n",
    "|:------|:---------------|\n",
    "| `MinThreshold` / `MaxThreshold` | Observed price band of the dense cluster — no hand-tuning |\n",
    "| `QuantityOfEAInUOM` | The UOM quantity this cluster represents (e.g. 12 for BX/12) |\n",
    "| `MeanEA` | Per-each price anchor, used when no WAP entry exists |\n",
    "\n",
    "Because outliers are excluded, the clusters are precise. A product with a BX/12 at\n",
    "$120–$180 and an EA at $10–$15 produces two separate clean clusters — not one wide band.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Part 2 — The Proximity Inference Formula\n",
    "\n",
    "Once DBSCAN clusters exist, Step 5 must decide which cluster best explains the file's\n",
    "`PriceUOM`. The core insight: **price operates on a log scale**. A $5 difference matters\n",
    "far more at a $10 product than a $10,000 product.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step A — Log-distance from cluster edge\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"formula-box\">\n",
    "<span class=\"hl\">logPrice</span> = log₁₀(<span class=\"key\">max</span>(PriceUOM, 0.0001))<br>\n",
    "<span class=\"hl\">logLo</span>    = log₁₀(<span class=\"key\">max</span>(MinThreshold, 0.0001))<br>\n",
    "<span class=\"hl\">logHi</span>    = log₁₀(<span class=\"key\">max</span>(MaxThreshold, 0.0001))<br>\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "<span class=\"hl\">logDist</span>  = <span class=\"val\">0</span>                       <span class=\"cmt\">← price is inside the cluster band</span><br>\n",
    "         = logPrice − logHi          <span class=\"cmt\">← price is above the band</span><br>\n",
    "         = logLo − logPrice          <span class=\"cmt\">← price is below the band</span>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "If `PriceUOM` falls **inside** the cluster, `logDist = 0` — a perfect match.\n",
    "Outside, the distance grows as the log ratio of the price to the nearest edge.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step B — Gaussian proximity score\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"formula-box\">\n",
    "<span class=\"hl\">proximityScore</span> = <span class=\"key\">exp</span>(−0.5 × (logDist / <span class=\"val\">LOG_EPS</span>)²)<br>\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "<span class=\"cmt\">where  LOG_EPS = 0.25  (≈ 1.78× tolerance from the cluster edge)</span>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "This is a **Gaussian kernel on log-price space**. At `logDist = 0` the score is exactly 1.0.\n",
    "At a 1.78× price deviation from the edge the score falls to ~0.37. At 2× it collapses to\n",
    "~0.02 — effectively zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "<div class=\"insight-box\">\n",
    "<div class=\"insight-label\">Why This Mirrors Analyst Reasoning</div>\n",
    "<div class=\"insight-text\">\n",
    "Analysts manually verify a UOM by asking: <em>\"is this price in the right ballpark for this product and pack size?\"</em> A BX/10 should cost ~10× a single unit. If the file shows 3× or 20× off, the analyst rejects it. The proximity score formalises this intuition — prices inside the cluster score 1.0, prices slightly outside drop gracefully, and wildly mismatched prices collapse to near zero. Working in <strong>log space</strong> means the tolerance is proportional (a 50% deviation at $10 and a 50% deviation at $10,000 are treated identically), which is exactly how analysts think about pricing.\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "</div>\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step C — Four candidate pools\n",
    "\n",
    "Step 5 scores up to four candidate sources and picks the highest:\n",
    "\n",
    "| # | Source | Signal | Min score required |\n",
    "|:--|:-------|:-------|:-------------------|\n",
    "| 1 | **DBSCAN cluster** | Density-derived from purchase history | None (primary) |\n",
    "| 2 | **Known Product UOM (WAP)** | Weighted-average price from history | None |\n",
    "| 3 | **EA/1 WAP** | Per-each price derived from WAP ÷ qty | None |\n",
    "| 4 | **File UOM × WAP** | File-stated qty × per-each WAP | **0.85** (stricter — file labels unreliable) |\n",
    "\n",
    "The row is assigned if the winning score is **≥ 0.30**; otherwise it exits unrecognized.\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Winner-Source Breakdown"
   ]
